stylometry: The most important factors to look at are ordering and holding costs. If you order small amounts frequently then you are going to see higher ordering costs. Alternatively if you order large amounts infrequently, you will see larger holding costs. In the case of a warehouse scenario, you may reach a point where your warehous is full and no more inventory can come in, so knowing the limits of how much you can feasibly store would be important as well. Overall it is management's job to analyze what the best timing and size of an order should be, in order to reduce overall costs.
